content: Online Renju Class will start the Analyses lesson.
Today is my last day to be the headmaster of Analyses department.
The new headmaster will be yyfcsd
sorry, yy it wasn't meant for you :-)))
and many good teachers will begin to teach Analyses lessons.
For example, next week, on June 1, you can enjoy Mr Kawamura's lesson,
The teacher from june 15 will be decided by yyfcsd
yes, and students will be more active also since june,
because 1 month idle rule will apply for all renjuclass members -
if the idleness of a student (no cp change) is more than 30 days, the name will be erased from list.
so, students must be constantly active, to stay alive in renjuclass
it will give good opportunities for new members to join.
does it mean that teachers will correct all the hws in time as well?
even teacher cannot correct all in time,
teacher can check what hws were received,
and at least add the sending cp (1 cp) first
and later add the remaining cps
then it will solve the idle check problem,
and gives some time for teacher, if he is too busy
is it ok for yy and lu?
the idle time counter will be shown in student list,
so please check your status then regularly,
and if your idleness is approaching to 30 days, then be careful
are there any exceptions? e.g. if a student explains before the 30 days
yes, basically it is possible to make exceptions.
we can discuss in detail later, maybe
the system will select the list of expired names to be deleted,
RT has a right to uncheck some names before submitting deletion
so, if someone is in some vacation,
or some problem, and it has been agreed with RT,
he can get some short extension
at least, now you are aware of idea.
the clock will start ticking from june 1.
any new department taught by RT?
but it doesnt mean I will never teach there.
I will occasionally teach in Analyses and maybe even Theory dept,
but my focus will be for advanced students of renjuclass from now,
it will be explained more in June

Today, one more game about Team WC.
What you see on the board is a famous Russian gambling variant.
Most of Russian team's players used it quite often during Team WC,
For some reason, their opponents failed to win as black one after another,
and whats even worse - they losed so fast, sometimes in less than 20 moves.
The variant was based on concept:
This 5th is sure win, so they would not keep it.
Since until recently, the theories claim 5-i7 to be win also,
they decided to challenge these claims
Some gamble style lovers, such as Chingin, Klimashin have made some deep analyses here.
is anyone here in this room who knows black win here?
then perhaps we let Author show it.
please think of white next move
i will wait until every student says his/her next move
the idea of 3rd department (Research Lab) is, there are no such idle names as now.
because they all thought its no win.
so all kinds of strange moves were used.
so, we had no chance to find out
what 10th move the Russians had prepared.
so we need to keep guessing here.
maybe ASV knows more about the gamble plan of Russians?
we were in different teams with chingin :)
yeah, but I saw Russia-2 also used this variant
so i know little about this variant
all i know, it's black win, but must be very difficult
yeah, but they were so brave to try against anyone
knowing that people have enough time to prepare
but they played it again and again,
ok now i know how to play in high league :)
difficult to remember how to win
maybe this 15th wasn't analysed by chingin..
so who wants easy point in ORC against chugunkin, here it is
seems this 10th move was solved in China last year by Shanghai players
they have broken the russian puzzle
In Shanghai Meijing Opening,I use this 10 to fight Mr.Yamaguchi :)
i enjoy this because its new for me too
did yamaguchi find win during game?
before I used this variant in 2004 Shanghai Meijing Opening, few people know this. It's hard to find the answer during the real game
so you studied every possible 20th move here?
well done author, we are proud of you
Kozhin have only one short diagram with this 5th, telling that it's black win :)
imagine you are a strong player,
you have good tactical and calculation skill,
but you dont know the win after 5-i7
what do you decided to do in this moment?
i9 maybe leads to positional game,somehow ?
yes, a strong and experienced player would try to avoid complications,
trying to find some positional style outcome,
This pattern actually offers plenty of ways.
There are many possibilities to come out successfully as black here.
And Russia-1 teams knows that Estonian team would use this tactics,
so, although we waited eagerly for this variant,
in the match against us, they did not use this variant in any table,
furthermore, they dragged Chingin off the table,
so, our tactical preparation for this variant could not be tested, pity
who wants to challenge this move as white,
so, instead of spending days to find win after 5-i7,
our team spent 10 minutes, to prepaer 5-i5,
who wants to finish it, say me
a good moment to show some thinking and attack
well done, nice show by yy and virag
So, this was just a reminder to you,
where you are not fully sure of theoretical win.
I am too lazy to learn all those branches,
so I usually use moves in style of 5-i5
need to analyse a bit more
in the game, more time to think
more peaceful style fans can go here
you can try at home some other 5th moves too,
5-I9 is also very strong ,I had a game with yyfcsd in ORC
but what I want to show you today is this:
A move that Salnikov used against Sushkov during team WC.
It looks as if black is preparing suicide,
there is no easy move for white here at all.
It was a shocking news for Sushkov.
Namely, in standard situations, white should be able to go to g7 here.
on the left from stone 10 there are 5 free fields,
and Sushkov realized it too late.
Now, black can use such wonderful 13th move.
Sushkov spent most of his thinking time,
if we cut off the 15th line, can black still win?
paobably not, as i11 not black win :)
smaller space, no win or not easy
with the narrower space, white can find better defense than these 14 or 16
Maybe, Sushkov forgot about this shift,
therefore he should have tried this 10th move,
we studied this long time ago :)
and use the shift in white's favor this time.
while in i11 they can win here.
or 11-k5 which are effective in i11 opening,
So, Salnikov managed to trick Sushkov,
Of course, if white player wanted to use such gamble, and avoid 5-i8 problems,
then its better to use i9 opening instead of d8.
then there is no shift, compared to i11 opening.
can white play any other 8th move here?
this is not so important anyway.
We know how black has the proper win by theory,
and we also learned the positional style win today.
and the third example, as we saw just now,
its an example what may happen to gambling players,
if they are not ready for turn-offs from gambling paths by opponents.
So, Salnikov got important tactical win.
This was a bit difficult topic today,
especially for medium level students today,
but I hope, after you download this lesson file,
and replay it slowly at home,
